As you dig in, pay close attention to how you'll handle "out of order" events; in a distributed system, the message sent first isn't always the one that arrives first.

Start with [Use The Index, Luke!](https://use-the-index-luke.com/) to nail the B-Tree mental model before you touch implementation-specific internals. Most developers treat indexes as "go-fast" buttons, but this resource forces you to understand the [Anatomy of an Index](https://use-the-index-luke.com/sql/anatomy), which is the prerequisite for understanding how databases actually navigate data on disk.

Once you have the physical structure down, move to the [PostgreSQL Tutorial](https://www.postgresql.org/docs/current/tutorial.html) to bridge the gap between simple queries and the transactional concepts required for Multi-Version Concurrency Control (MVCC). Understanding how Write-Ahead Logging (WAL) and MVCC work requires a solid grasp of transaction isolation, which these official docs provide without the fluff of a secondary tutorial.

